BODYCOLUMN: 1/Background information normalising // // the difficulty of quitting smoking, and // // smoking cues which make it difficult. // // Background research suggesting how // // music may provide an additional // // strategy to help smokers quit. // // Selecting the emotional cue most // associated with smoking from a list. // Explanation of the two-dimensional // valence-arousal model of emotions. // // Clicking where previously-selected // // emotional cue lies on valence/arousal // // chart. // // Smoking to change feelings, and how // // the feeling changes in terms of valence/ // // arousal. // Indicating how emotional smoking // // cue changes in valence/arousal after // // smoking, by selecting “increases/ // // decreases/stays the same” from // // dropdown boxes. // // Asking participants to consider // // what music would match the target, // // post-smoking emotion, followed by // // explanation that personally-meaningful // // music works best. // // Writing the features of their chosen // // music important in changing emotions, // // in a free-response text box. // // // // Strategies for listening to music in // // various locations/situations, instead of // // smoking. // // Writing ideas for how music-listening // // could be used to change feelings when // // an emotional cue induces smoking // // urges, in a free-response text box. // // Creating a “quitting playlist”. // Writing the first three songs and artists // to be added to the quitting playlist. //
